{"text": "254\n\nBy appropriate gauge we can assume without loss of generality that f(n) is real and non-negative. so we can write\n\nf(n) =\n\np\n\ng(n)\n\n(51.11)\n\nFrom the definition of \u02c6a it follows that\n\n\u02c6a\u2020\u02c6a n\u27e9= g(n) n\u27e9\n\n(51.12)\n\nand therefore\n\n\u02c6a\u2020\u02c6a = g (\u02c6n)\n\n(51.13)\n\nThere are 3 cases of interest\n\n\u2022 The raising/lowering is unbounded (\u2212\u221e< n < \u221e)\n\n\u2022 The raising/lowering is bounded from one side (say 0 \u2264n < \u221e)\n\n\u2022 The raising/lowering is bounded from both sides (say 0 \u2264n < N)\n\nThe simplest choice for g(n) in the first case is\n\ng(n) = 1\n\n(51.14)\n\nIn such a case \u02c6a becomes the translation operator, and the spectrum of n stretches from \u2212\u221eto \u221e. The simplest\n\nchoice for g(n) in the second case is\n\ng(n) = n\n\n(51.15)\n\nthis leads to the same algebra as in the case of an harmonic oscillator. The simplest choice for g(n) in the third case\n\nis\n\ng(n) = (N \u2212n)n\n\n(51.16)\n\nHere it turns out that the algebra is the same as that for angular momentum. To see that it is indeed like that define\n\nm = n \u2212N \u22121\n\n2\n\n= \u2212s, . . . , +s\n\n(51.17)\n\nwhere s = (N \u22121)/2. Then it is possible to write\n\ng(m) = s(s + 1) \u2212m(m + 1)\n\n(51.18)\n\nIn the next sections we are going to discuss the \u201cBosonic\u201d case N = \u221ewith g(n) = n, and the \u201cFermionic\u201d case\n\nN = 2 with g(n) = n(1 \u2212n). Later we are going to argue that these are the only two possibilities that are relevant\n\nto the description of many body occupation.\n\n255\n\n\u2212s\n\n0\n\n1\n\n2\n\nN\n\n...\n\nn\n\nm\n\ndim=N\n\nFermions\n\n+s\n\nN\u22121\n\ng(n)\n\nBosons\n\nIt is worthwhile to note that the algebra of \u201cangular momentum\u201d can be formally obtained from the Bosonic algebra\n\nusing a trick due to Schwinger. Let us define two Bosonic operators a1 and a2, and\n\nc\u2020\n\n=\n\na\u2020\n\n2a1\n\n(51.19)\n\nThe c\u2020 operator moves a particle from site 1 to site 2. Consider how c and c\u2020 operate within the subspace of (N \u22121)\n\nparticle states.", "embedding": [0.009450511, -0.03278378, 0.037880816, -0.011216486, -0.003632427, -0.026943022, 0.024928505, -0.05137002, -0.048252717, 0.071295716, 0.06994634, 0.0051044314, -0.012421398, -0.032262187, 0.014804914, 0.020900184, -0.02216863, -0.0076246173, -0.07870025, 0.024154996, 0.04941772, 0.005735886, -0.08724344, -0.0086596375, -0.031104121, 0.039669707, 0.045423, 0.022512993, 0.050264575, 0.025128273, -0.011258969, -0.03163641, 0.021094393, -0.019620825, -0.02543827, -0.01768499, -0.013897194, -0.038455658, 0.033674885, -0.0124504585, 0.0415051, -0.010060576, 0.010518375, -0.027090512, -0.049845275, -0.020975117, -0.018081723, -0.009780028, -0.019196147, -0.0769856, -0.005697303, -0.0068395045, 0.03392735, -0.055644117, -0.040606994, -0.022089131, 0.007110056, 0.024174698, -0.043749828, 0.024933757, 0.028148966, -0.000446594, -0.016217167, -0.05118458, 0.014299652, 0.03986871, -0.011971675, 0.03473421, 0.005019718, -0.071807705, 0.007137987, 0.03832341, -0.04631835, 0.019249396, -0.026555518, 0.050272565, 0.016420003, -0.029120415, -0.05357254, 0.008418194, 0.0062132007, 0.0021276693, -0.027187398, 0.01480851, 0.00075438514, 0.005984178, 0.016392995, -0.008018283, -0.015070142, -0.038903307, 0.0004485795, 0.045998905, -0.015676642, -0.0062052687, 0.03243511, 0.004394895, -0.003803916, 0.052485257, 0.03740359, -0.014682203, 0.034874506, 0.035659645, -0.023656322, 0.038937774, -0.023575839, 0.05416383, -0.014659786, 0.03848403, -0.021564227, -0.02915114, 0.014301075, -0.03385711, 0.027488384, 0.0051375157, 0.015405427, 0.04583907, 0.0014211467, 0.04334295, -0.030876184, -0.010974916, 0.024043363, 0.019409966, 0.047315247, 0.017554225, -0.0060625337, -0.0002535795, -0.0005373433, 0.011956855, -0.07113139, 0.016986294, 0.043061644, -0.006726956, 6.886057e-05, -0.020927144, -0.029327381, 0.027715093, -0.0047